Metadata
Study Information
Hypotheses
H*: A positive relation will be found between openness to experiences and leadership experiences
Statistical test: Structural equation modeling (SEM)
Expected pattern of results: Openness to experiences will predict leadership experiences
Design Plan
Study type
Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. This includes surveys, “natural experiments,” and
regression discontinuity designs.
Blinding
No blinding is involved in this study.
Is there any additional blinding in this study?
As this is an observational study, we will not need to use blinding (i.e., there is not treatment versus control group and researchers will not interact with
participants directly).
Study design
This is a replication study of Popper et al. (2009) from the Leadership Quarterly. As such, we attempt to replicate procedures as much as possible from this study.
We follow the same methods of Popper and Amit (2009) with slight modifications to sample and procedures of data gathering. Their all-male sample was drawn
from active-duty Israeli military members, which we will not be able to access. Thus, we will use a US sample of men with military experience (may include active
duty, reserve, or veterans), which we do not have reason to believe will be substantially different from the original study sample population. Popper and Amit
(2009) also used survey administration but provided surveys directly to sample participants while we will obtain our sample using the Prolific online data
collection platform in order to reach the desired number of participants meeting our inclusion criteria.
In our replication, we recruit from a large electronic database, Prolific, and set the following criteria: participants must be 1) men, 2) over the age of 18, 3) have
experience survey in the U.S. military, and 4) have an Prolific study approval rate of 90% (to inspire quality responses). We are targeting 671 respondents based
on the power analysis provided by the SCORE team below. 
We are imposing the following custom qualifications on our Prolific recruitment: 
1.
In Prolific, we have the ability to screen participants with “custom qualifications” - We will only include those designated as having U.S. military experience
and study approval rates of 90%. In the Qualtrics survey, we will require participants to respond to a series of questions asking about their military experience
(e.g., active versus veteran status, military branch, length of service). If they respond they do NOT have military experience, they are taken to the end of the
survey. 
2.
In Qualtrics, we will also ask participants if they identify as men and are over the age of 18. If they answer no, they are taken to the end of the survey. 
Upon inclusion, participants will be directed to an online survey (SURVEY LINK) that includes all the measures assembled from Popper and Amit (2009) that are
relevant to testing Hypotheses 4. They will be compensated $1.20 through Prolific upon survey completion.
Measures:
Insufficient information is provided in the Popper and Amit (2009) manuscript to reconstruct the exact scales used for attachment style, openness to experience,
and leader experiences. As such, we have tried to contact the authors, but have not yet received response. We will continue to await response but have also
constructed measures for the study below based on the information available in the published study.
Attachment Style. Popper and Amit (2009) do not provide the items they used to measure attachment style, but they did reference Hazan and Shaver (1987) and
Shaver, Belsky, and Brennan (2000) regarding how they constructed their attachment scale. They also noted they used 13 total items: 6 items to represent the
anxious dimension and 7 items to represent the avoidant dimension, with lower total scores indicating secure attachment style. As we cannot know which items
were used to construct either scale, we will use the items used in Shaver, Belsky, and Brennan (which were pulled from Collins and Read, 1990). These items
include six items for the anxiety scale and twelve items for the two facets of avoidance: closeness and dependence. Items are scored on a 5-point Likert-type
