Data Analysis
While Popper and Amit (2009) utilized Amos 5 software for their analyses, we will test the hypothesis using Structural Equation Modeling in R Statistical Software.
This represents a departure in analysis tool only (i.e., analysis procedures will be the same as the original study) and we have no reason to expect the difference
in software to have an effect on results. The original study applied a parceling approach to aggregate latent variable indicators stating,  “A rule of thumb is that a
measurement model with three indicators per latent construct is ideal, and it can carry up to five indicators without estimation difficulties” (p. 755) and citing
Bagozzi and Heatherton (1994). However, substantial advances in computational software abilities have been made since 2009, and R software has no issue
estimating models with more than 5 indicators per latent variable and parceling is a controversial practice in structural equation modeling. Thus, we will replicate
the random parceling procedure to aggregate latent variable indicators for use in testing the structural model. In addition, we will also run a separate analysis
where we include all indicators for each latent variable in our  model estimation and provide results for both sets of analyses. Paths will be estimated with
Leadership Experience as the dependent variable, Attachment as the independent variable and Trait Anxiety and Openness to Experience as the two mediator
variables.
