Sample size
The target analytic sample size is 671 participants as determined by COS power analysis.
To achieve the target analytic sample size, we anticipate the need to collect a slightly larger sample size to account for any necessary deletion due to insufficient
effort responding or extensive missing data. The target sample size for recruitment is thus 700 participants. Insufficient effort responding will be determined by
reviewing time to complete the survey: participants that complete in less than 30 seconds will be removed from the data. Participants missing more than 10% of
data per scale will have their responses removed from the data, as will participants who fail both of 2 attention check items.
Sample size rationale
Power calculations were conducted in accordance with the guidelines of the Social Sciences Replication Project (SSRP). However, instead of carrying out two
rounds of data collection to achieve the stage 1 sample size target followed by the stage 2 sample size target as in Phase 1 of SCORE, in Phase 2 only one data
collection effort will be carried out to achieve a single target analytic sample size.
All replications will aim to achieve the target analytic sample size, which is determined by a power analysis achieving 90% power to detect 50% of the original
effect size (formally referred to as the Stage 2 sample size). However, if this sample size is not attainable for the replicating lab, the sample size will instead be
calculated by achieving 90% power to detect 75% of the original effect size (formally referred to as the Stage 1 sample size).
For this study, because collecting the Stage 2 sample size would not be feasible under SCORE’s allowable budget, the Stage 1 sample size (which is powered to
detect 75% of the original effect size) will instead be collected. The Stage 1 sample size for this study is 671 participants.
Documentation of the power analysis conducted for this replication is available at the following view-only link: https://osf.io/q8xpr/?
view_only=665f77d6e7ed416fa8877edeaccdf7e3.
Stopping rule
The planned analytic sample size is 671 participants. The target sample size for recruitment is 700 participants. After achieving this sample, sampling will stop
and planned analyses will be run.
Variables
Manipulated variables
As this is an observational study, there are no manipulated variables.
No files selected
Measured variables
Variables to be included in this study are described below. As we are using structural equation modeling as the method of analysis, we must capture all study
variables previously captured in Popper & Amit (2009) to obtain the target effect size. The independent and dependent variable are labelled as such below:
Attachment (included in the structural model) - We will use the items used in Shaver, Belsky, and Brennan (2000, which were pulled from Collins and Read, 1990).
These items include six items for the anxiety scale and twelve items for the two facets of avoidance: closeness and dependence. Items are scored on a 5-point
Likert-type scale from where 1 = not at all characteristic, 2 = somewhat uncharacteristic, 3 = neither characteristic nor uncharacteristic, 4 = somewhat
characteristic, and 5 = very characteristic. Higher scores indicate more secure attachment style.
Anxiety (Included in the structural model) - We will measure trait anxiety using the same strategies as Popper and Amit (2009) in using the STAI for adults.
Respondents will be provided the following instructions: "Read each statement and then blacken the appropriate circle to the right of the statement to indicate
how you feel right now, that is, at this moment. There are no right or wrong answers. Do not spend too much time on any one statement but give the answer
which seems to describe your present feelings best." They will then indicate their responses from 1 = Not at all, 2 = Somewhat, 3 = Moderately so, and 4 = Very
much so. Higher scores indicate higher trait anxiety.
Openness to Experience (independent variable) - The International Personality Item Pool (IPIP) has 20-item abbreviated NEO Openness to Experience measure
that is commonly used in social science research. Thus, we will use this version of the NEO Openness to Experience measure. The following instructions will be
given to participants "Describe yourself as you generally are now, not as you wish to be in the future. Describe yourself as you honestly see yourself, in relation to
other people you know of the same sex as you are, and roughly your same age. So that you can describe yourself in an honest manner, your responses will be
kept in absolute confidence. Indicate for each statement whether it is 1. Very Inaccurate, 2. Moderately Inaccurate, 3. Neither Accurate Nor Inaccurate, 4.
Moderately Accurate, or 5. Very Accurate as a description of you." Higher scores indicate higher Openness to Experience.
Leadership Experiences (dependent variable)- We will measure leadership experiences using the same strategies as Popper and Amit (2009). The scale used for
this construct was created by Popper and Amit (2009) specifically for their study, and was designed to capture the early-life experiences with influence and
