leadership roles of participants prior to their joining the military. Popper and Amit provided the questions for the scale. As such, participants will be asked to read
a set of seven statements about their past leadership experiences and rate each statement regarding the level of experience they have with each. Popper and
Amit did not provide instructions for their scale, however, so we created instructions to ensure participants are reflecting on their experiences through high
school and prior to joining the military, which is consistent with the desired time period put forth by Popper and Amit for this scale. Participants will see the
instructions, " For the following statements, please think about your early life experiences through grade school education and up to high school graduation (i.e.,
prior to joining the military). Please select the answer below that best describes the extent of experience you had with the topic in each statement during this
early life time period." Items will be rated on a scale of 1 to 4 where 1 = Hardly any experience, 2 = Some experience, 3 = Moderate experience, and 4 = Rich
experience. Popper and Amit (2009) only supplied the scale anchors at 1 and 4 for this measure, so we had to create the response options for 2 and 3. Higher
scores indicate greater extent of early leadership experience.
Other- As we are using a sample of U.S. men with military service, our sample differs from the original study in that 1) participants will not be Israeli, and 2)
Participants will not have served in the Israeli military. As such, we will collect the following additional demographic information on our sample so that we may
describe and account for the different population, though these variables will not be included in the hypothesis testing:
Age
Race
Highest Education level (Some High School- did not graduate, High school, Bachelor's degree, Graduate school, Post-graduate work)
Type of military service (e.g., army, navy, air force, etc.)
Length of military service
Status of military service (active duty, reserve, or veteran)
We acknowledge that certain differences in the original study’s sample and our proposed sample may result in different observations of effects. For example, it is
possible the effect size between openness to experience and leadership experiences will be larger in the American population due to selection effects related to
the voluntary nature of American military service (Israeli military service is compulsory). Thus, higher baseline levels of early life leadership experiences may be
present for the American sample compared to the Israeli sample, possibly resulting in a stronger observed relationship (i.e., greater than B = .34). Should the
effect size for our sample be observed to be substantially higher than that observed in the Popper & Amit (2009) study, we will discuss possible reasons for this in
our report. This difference in sample should not interfere with the potential for replicability, however.
No files selected
Indices
We are using structural equation modeling to analyze the data and will follow Popper & Amit’s strategy for creating 3 random parcels per scale for parameter
estimation. Thus, each of the three parcels for each scale (attachment, trait anxiety, openness to experience, and leadership experiences) represents a composite
score of the items randomly assigned to that parcel. Further, to run correlations of all study variables, composite scores will be created for each of the four
measured variables included in the structural model (attachment, trait anxiety, openness to experience, and leadership experiences)
No files selected
Analysis Plan
Statistical models
For the purposes of SCORE, to test H* and attempt to replicate the H* statistical evidence we will use structural equation modeling with randomized parceling, as
this was the method used by Popper & Amit (2009). However, we will also test the structural model without parceling the items as a robustness check.
No files selected
Transformations
We will not transform our measured variables.
Inference criteria
For this study, Model 1 was retained as the best fitting model from the Popper & Amit original study and the effect size generated for H4 was B = .34. Thus
successful replication should be represented by a statistically significant positive beta coefficient for the relationship between openness to experience and leader
experiences.
Data exclusion
If participants indicate they do not meet any of the inclusion criteria (military experience, U.S. resident, male), they will be excluded from analyses.
If participants demonstrate insufficient effort responding as evidenced by marking all items across scales as the same response, they will be excluded from
analyses (e.g., the openness to experience scale should vary among given certain items that are reverse-coded).
Participants who finish the survey in less than 30 seconds will be excluded from the data given the length of the survey.
We will also include two attention check items. Participants who fail both attention check items will be removed from the survey
Missing data
If participants are missing substantial responses (more than 60% missing per scale), they will be excluded from analyses. The mean score for all items on a scale
will be imputed for missing data given participants completed at least 90% of items per scale.
Exploratory analysis
Not applicable
